-rnp" class="fai-CopilotMessage__content r1izxv8h ___7qar2c0 fcthzvy"><div dir="auto"><div class="___1vve6yh f22iagw f1vx9l62 f122n59 f3bhgqh f1mnxvew fly5x3f"><div class="___j4vmuw0 f22iagw f1vx9l62 f1869bpl fly5x3f fbc6vix"><div tabindex="-1" data-testid="loading-message"><div><div id="chatMessageResponse-rnn" class="___1yop6mf f336tjw f9ijwd5 fz7g6wx fod5ikn f1s184ao"><div dir="auto" aria-hidden="false" class="___1j4t0a1 f1lmfglv f1abmfm4" data-testid="markdown-reply"><div class="___stpibi0 f22iagw f1vx9l62 fk15e71 f1k953kz f137keqj f1rncccw f1stllg3 f1w4kmmc f1tric3v f10dk5ic fx8cdsv f16nlwsl f1eookvz fhjrts3 fqugt2f f10km5jb f18d18k8 f1v1vhmp f1hdmul3 f198vjnp f2dshw1 fjpjndq fnmj2pj ffrrb40 f1mon110 fhajzam fimndk6 fxv4dng fb1rn9k f59wlhv f1xmfh30 f18yf5o5 fmr6chf fw8qy2q ff161sd f1qr7t77 f1yyogn1 foogchg fp5872b f1tpb8gf f1hdgrc8 f1vatr43 frkxccd f9pdzkb f158oiaz ft5kggy f5l4ui7 f13j03li f18xdoka f8off4e f1go6zfc f128n2ra f1jpxw2j f1lwd9n0 fy0b8hm f1g2633v fx4kvgi fkvolse f1gxrt3a f1os76ua f1js9cnw f1g87ej0 freluf8 f1yggaq6 f2i3chp f1151osp florpoh f35kzfz ftp9m57 f1e288vi fz62hnz fixvuys f1nmofwh fc1c6mv f18a2er7 fhvkrdl fhxnn68 f1oce4bo fvhlfan f7tc0t0 f1ngf1n2 ffrzq6x f1yjiq2m f1aqdgql f1huvaf f10ij78l f1k94sa4 fkmfumq f1jvzkyl f1eu24ob f1xbfc1f fmf0lwf f107dsy8 f3w566c f4648sl f13zpkng f7unjfp f8p1rz fzu6h1w f1i1bi6h f1smo7hi f1sk1xod f1kgogdq f1gjktkp ft608jz f19dd9cz fg3xr24 fhd155k f1b8gl2e fg4b9ou flb4lo fdicbfk fgwcyh1 f1jbds0d f1fb9uea f1stuka4 fcrtu6g fwqh0xn f11w66yg f6e0e65 f1vvgu0 f1607507 f1m9bycv f1ntoah8 f1b694rt faql4r2 fpjuhzh fmavl6h"><p>Short answer: <strong>YES — apply.</strong><br>
This role is an even <em>better</em> fit for you than the hospital hardware PM role, and here’s why:</p>
<h1>⭐ Overall Fit Score: <strong>9/10</strong></h1>
<p>This role hits your strengths (SaaS, healthcare/finance ops, client-facing implementations, workflows, requirements, training) <strong>without requiring 5+ years of formal implementation PM</strong> or PMP. It’s more “hands-on implementation + business analyst + PM,” which aligns directly with what you already do in Revenue Integrity + Cloudmed + FinThrive + Lawson + workflow build.</p>
<p>This is a GREAT stepping stone into tech implementation.</p>
<hr>
<h1>Why This Role Fits You Perfectly</h1>
<h2>✅ <strong>1. It values implementation, not pure PM seniority</strong></h2>
<p>You already:</p>
<ul>
<li>Lead cross-functional work</li>
<li>Do requirements gathering (Cloudmed → Coding → RI workflow fixes)</li>
<li>Build and optimize workflows</li>
<li>Coordinate UAT and corrections</li>
<li>Document logic, create training/jobaids</li>
<li>Manage multi-department deliverables</li>
</ul>
<p>This is exactly what implementation specialists do.</p>
<h2>✅ <strong>2. It’s SaaS + operations-focused — your sweet spot</strong></h2>
<p>You’ve been doing:</p>
<ul>
<li>Charge workflow optimization</li>
<li>Audit logic configuration</li>
<li>Data integrity oversight</li>
<li>Multi‑system mapping (Craneware, Lawson, Spacetrax)</li>
</ul>
<p>Translates directly into:</p>
<ul>
<li>Salesforce config</li>
<li>Lending workflow mapping</li>
<li>Data conversion QA</li>
<li>Ticket writing</li>
<li>System behavior validation</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Your skills will translate very well.</strong></p>
<h2>✅ <strong>3. You already gather requirements &amp; translate them into builds</strong></h2>
<p>A huge part of this job is:</p>
<ul>
<li>“Ask key questions to understand client workflows”</li>
<li>“Break down complex processes”</li>
<li>“Write detailed tickets with acceptance criteria”</li>
<li>“Configure the system based on needs”</li>
</ul>
<p>This is <em>exactly</em> what you do every day when:</p>
<ul>
<li>You determine Cloudmed logic</li>
<li>You validate missing charges</li>
<li>You map revenue codes</li>
<li>You route audits with acceptance criteria</li>
<li>You write RI/QA compliance-grade notes</li>
</ul>
<p>You’re basically doing <strong>business analyst + implementation</strong> work right now.</p>
<h2>✅ <strong>4. Salesforce experience is preferred, not required</strong></h2>
<p>You can learn flows, objects, fields, and Lightning pages very fast — you’re already comfortable with:</p>
<ul>
<li>Cloudmed</li>
<li>Spacetrax</li>
<li>Lawson item masters</li>
<li>Craneware CDM logic</li>
<li>MS4/Cerner workflows</li>
</ul>
<p>Those systems are harder than Salesforce.</p>
<p>A Salesforce Admin cert later would boost you a LOT.</p>
<h2>✅ <strong>5. No healthcare EMR requirement</strong></h2>
<p>Unlike hospital PM roles, this FINTECH role doesn’t care about Cerner/Epic experience.<br>
They care about:</p>
<ul>
<li>Process mapping</li>
<li>Client onboarding</li>
<li>Config + requirements</li>
<li>Data accuracy</li>
<li>Communication</li>
</ul>
<p>All your strengths.</p>
<h2>👍 Extra note: The salary may align with your goals</h2>
<p>Implementation Specialists in fintech SaaS often pay <strong>$85k–$120k</strong>, sometimes more at high-growth companies.<br>
Not guaranteed, but this is likely in your target range.</p>
<hr>
<h1>Potential Gaps (and how to cover them)</h1>
<h2>⚠️ “2+ years of lending industry experience”</h2>
<p>This is the only real gap. But you can overcome it with:</p>
<p><strong>Transferable domain logic:</strong><br>
Revenue cycle ≈ lending lifecycle</p>
<ul>
<li>audits = underwriting</li>
<li>compliance logic = lending compliance</li>
<li>workflow dependencies = loan origination steps</li>
<li>data mapping = loan servicing data flows</li>
</ul>
<p>You just need to say:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>“My background is healthcare financial systems and compliance, which translates well into lending workflows because both rely on accurate data, multi-step approvals, regulated processes, and cross-functional dependencies.”</p>
</blockquote>
<h2>⚠️ Salesforce configuration</h2>
<p>Not required deeply — you can learn Lightning pages and Flows quickly.<br>
Emphasize:</p>
<ul>
<li>You’re actively learning tech</li>
<li>You’ve worked with complex multi-system configurations</li>
<li>You pick up platforms fast</li>
</ul>
<p>You can even mention your data analytics training.</p>
<hr>
<h1>How You Should Position Yourself in The Interview</h1>
<p><strong>“I specialize in translating messy, complex operational processes into clean, structured workflows and system configurations.”</strong></p>
<p><strong>“My healthcare revenue cycle background gives me deep experience with data accuracy, compliance, multi-step approvals, and cross‑functional implementation — all directly applicable to lending workflows.”</strong></p>
<p><strong>“I’m already familiar with writing clear requirements, building logic, coordinating testing, and managing client expectations.”</strong></p>
<p><strong>“I’m actively transitioning into SaaS implementation and have been training in data analytics and system workflows to prepare for roles exactly like this.”</strong></p>
<hr>
<h1>Should You Apply?</h1>
<p><strong>Absolutely yes.</strong><br>
This is the type of role that finally gets you OUT of hospital operations and INTO the tech implementation career you’ve been trying to break into.</p>
<p>And unlike the other PM roles:</p>
<ul>
<li>It doesn’t require 5+ years PM</li>
<li>It doesn’t require hardware experience</li>
<li>It values learning and configuration</li>
<li>It fits your career pivot</li>
<li>It’s more entry/mid-level SaaS implementation</li>
<li>You’re already doing 70% of this work in RI</li>
</ul>
<p>This is exactly how you enter tech.</p>
<hr>
<h1>If you want:</h1>
<p>I can create for you:<br>
✅ A <strong>tailored resume</strong> for this job<br>
✅ A <strong>FUNDINGO-specific cover letter</strong><br>
✅ A <strong>project list</strong> that looks like tech implementation work<br>
✅ A <strong>mock interview script</strong><br>
Just tell me what you want next.</p>
