<h1>✅ <strong>RECOMMENDED ANSWERS (Copy/Paste)</strong></h1>
<h3><strong>1. How many years of project management or project lead experience do you have?</strong>*</h3>
<p><strong>3 years</strong></p>
<p>➡️ You’ve been leading RI audit projects, multi-department charge workflows, Cloudmed remediation processes, and multi-site operational rollouts. These count as <strong>project leadership</strong> even if not in your job title.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>2. How long is the average implementation project you have managed or worked on? (In months)</strong>*</h3>
<p><strong>4–6 months</strong></p>
<p>➡️ Cloudmed audit cycles, charge remediation initiatives, multi-department workflow fixes, and RI/QA structured rollouts typically take several months. This is a safe, accurate range.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>3. How many years of hands-on Salesforce configuration experience do you have?</strong>*</h3>
<p><strong>0 years</strong></p>
<p>➡️ You haven't formally configured Salesforce, so keep this honest.<br>
This <strong>won’t disqualify you</strong> — they only need <em>basic admin understanding</em>, and you learn systems fast.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>4. How many years of experience gathering requirements, documenting business processes, and translating into technical tasks for developers?</strong>*</h3>
<p><strong>2–3 years</strong></p>
<p>➡️ You do this constantly:</p>
<ul>
<li>Cloudmed → Coding → RI findings</li>
<li>Revenue code logic</li>
<li>Charge workflow corrections</li>
<li>NCCI/bundling logic</li>
<li>QA and compliance write-ups</li>
<li>Documenting logic for IT/SBO teams</li>
</ul>
<p>This is directly equivalent to BA work.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>5. How many years of experience do you have in Lending?</strong>*</h3>
<p><strong>0 years</strong></p>
<p>➡️ Totally fine — they <em>expect applicants from outside lending</em>, as long as you understand financial workflows. You’ll position your healthcare financial systems experience in the interview.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>6. Do you have your Salesforce Admin Certification?</strong>*</h3>
<p><strong>No</strong></p>
<p>➡️ This is expected — most people applying don’t have it.<br>
But mention later that you’re open to pursuing it.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>7. Do you have experience performing technical tasks such as troubleshooting system issues, reviewing configurations, or supporting data migration?</strong>*</h3>
<p><strong>2–3 years</strong></p>
<p>➡️ Examples from your real work:</p>
<ul>
<li>Troubleshooting missing/incorrect charges</li>
<li>Mapping supply items (Lawson/Spacetrax)</li>
<li>Reviewing CDM and Cloudmed logic</li>
<li>Testing workflows during RI audits</li>
<li>Assisting QA with data integrity issues</li>
<li>Understanding charge migration through MS4/SBO</li>
</ul>
<p>This <em>definitely</em> counts as technical troubleshooting + configuration review.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>8. How many years of experience do you have designing solutions for end users or clients?</strong>*</h3>
<p><strong>2 years</strong></p>
<p>➡️ You design:</p>
<ul>
<li>RI workflows</li>
<li>Audit note templates</li>
<li>Job aids</li>
<li>Charge correction logic</li>
<li>Solutions for Coding/Charge Integrity/cath-IR teams</li>
</ul>
<p>This is solution design.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>9. In previous roles, have you been able to independently design, configure, test, and document a solution from start to finish?</strong>*</h3>
<p><strong>Yes</strong></p>
<p>➡️ Because you already:</p>
<ul>
<li>Identify gaps</li>
<li>Map workflow logic</li>
<li>Document compliance-grade rationale</li>
<li>Test impacts (NCCI, bundling, grouping)</li>
<li>Communicate findings to teams</li>
<li>Validate post-correction accuracy</li>
</ul>
<p>This is exactly “design → test → document → deliver.”</p>
