ntoah8 f1b694rt faql4r2 fpjuhzh fmavl6h"><p>You didn’t fail because you weren’t qualified — you only stumbled on <strong>CDM-specific questions</strong>, which is VERY common when coming from Revenue Integrity instead of CDM management.</p>
<p>Here’s the good news:</p>
<p><strong>You have the skills to pass these roles — you just need the right CDM language and frameworks ready.</strong><br>
I can help you build those answers so you NEVER get stuck on CDM questions again, whether it’s BRG, Berkeley Research Group, R1, Ensemble, Accenture, or Guidehouse.</p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ First — what they were <em>actually testing</em></h1>
<p>Even though the BRG role is “Associate, Implementation,” the interviewer pulled from their <strong>Healthcare Performance Improvement/Revenue Cycle</strong> playbook.</p>
<p>So they expected you to know:</p>
<h3>CDM 101</h3>
<ul>
<li>What it is</li>
<li>How it connects to charging, coding, and billing</li>
<li>How updates flow through systems</li>
<li>How audits tie back to CDM</li>
<li>How pricing, revenue codes, modifiers, NCCI, etc tie in</li>
</ul>
<h3>CDM Process Workflow</h3>
<p>They wanted you to articulate:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Request intake</strong></li>
<li><strong>CDM build</strong></li>
<li><strong>Mapping (GL, rev code, CPT/HCPCS, supply association)</strong></li>
<li><strong>Governance/Review</strong></li>
<li><strong>Testing in lower environments</strong></li>
<li><strong>Migration to production</strong></li>
<li><strong>Communication to downstream teams</strong></li>
<li><strong>Post-load QA</strong></li>
</ol>
<p>You actually <em>know</em> most of this because you do Cloudmed, FinThrive, Craneware, Spacetrax, ED fract audits, revenue codes, and CPT logic — but you needed the exact steps.</p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ Let’s give you a perfect CDM answer for next time</h1>
<p>This is the answer that will PASS you in any Revenue Cycle / Consulting CDM interview.</p>
<hr>
<h1>✔️ <strong>“Walk me through the CDM process” — Your new perfect answer</strong></h1>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>The CDM process is the lifecycle of how new or updated chargeable items move from request → build → validation → billing.</strong></p>
<p><strong>1. Intake:</strong> A department submits a request for a new charge, price change, supply, or update. We confirm the CPT/HCPCS code, revenue code, description, units, and the clinical use case.</p>
<p><strong>2. Research &amp; mapping:</strong> Validate coding logic, NCCI edits, coverage rules, component ownership (pro vs facility), appropriate rev code, pricing benchmarks, and supply/device links if applicable.</p>
<p><strong>3. Build in the CDM:</strong> Add or update the CDM line with the correct HCPCS/CPT, rev code, price, units, flags, and associated supply item numbers.</p>
<p><strong>4. Downstream mapping:</strong> Ensure the new code is mapped correctly to:<br>
– GL<br>
– Claims<br>
– Department dictionaries<br>
– Clinical systems (Cerner, MS4)<br>
– Supply systems (Lawson/Spacetrax)</p>
<p><strong>5. Testing:</strong> Validate that the charge posts correctly in lower environments based on triggers (order, documentation, diagnosis, charge event).</p>
<p><strong>6. Approval &amp; governance:</strong> Review with Pricing, Revenue Integrity, Coding, and Compliance before moving to production.</p>
<p><strong>7. Deployment:</strong> Move the CDM update into production and communicate the change to all stakeholders (coding, rev integrity, clinicians, billing).</p>
<p><strong>8. Post-load QA:</strong> Validate that the charge drops as expected on real accounts, ensuring no denials, NCCI conflicts, or missing charges.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>That is the standard CDM process used across nearly all consulting firms.</strong></p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ They also likely asked this:</h1>
<h2>❓ “What’s the difference between CDM, Coding, and Revenue Integrity?”</h2>
<p>Here’s the winning answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>CDM</strong> maintains chargeable items, prices, revenue codes, and mappings.<br>
<strong>Coding</strong> assigns ICD-10/CPT codes based on documentation.<br>
<strong>Revenue Integrity</strong> ensures charges are accurate, appropriate, complete, and compliant across workflows.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>And then include your real-world tie-in:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>“My RI background means I understand how errors in CDM build, rev codes, NCCI edits, or supply mapping create downstream issues like missing charges, incorrect bundling, incorrect HCPCS, or claim rejections.”</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That’s a PERFECT answer.</p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ They also probably asked this:</h1>
<h2>❓ “How does a CDM error affect billing?”</h2>
<p>Use this answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>“A CDM error can cause charges not to drop, incorrect revenue codes, mismatched CPT/HCPCS codes, NCCI denials, incorrect pricing, or wrong supply associations — all of which impact reimbursement and compliance.”</p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ They might’ve asked this too:</h1>
<h2>❓ “How do you ensure CDM integrity during an implementation?”</h2>
<p>Answer:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>“I ensure CDM integrity by validating mapping logic, running test claims, checking NCCI edits, confirming charge triggers, and performing pre- and post-migration QA to ensure charges appear correctly in MS4/Cerner and route to billing cleanly.”</p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
