You interviewed <strong>in January</strong> for BRG/Second Sight’s <em>Healthcare Performance Improvement (Revenue Cycle)</em> track (a RI/CDM/QA blend). Now you’re eyeing <strong>Associate, Implementation</strong> and you’re not sure if it’s a different department.</p>
<h3>Short answer</h3>
<p><strong>Yes—apply to Associate, Implementation.</strong><br>
Treat it as a <strong>different lane</strong> (implementation/technical delivery vs. RI/CDM consulting). It’s closer to product/tech onboarding and coordination—much more in your wheelhouse—and it won’t hinge on deep CDM minutiae like the last interview did.</p>
<p>Below is how to (1) confirm it’s a different org lane, (2) position your background for this posting, and (3) message recruiters so your previous interview doesn’t bias this application.</p>
<hr>
<h2>1) Is this a different department? How to check without guessing</h2>
<p>You don’t need to wait—do these two quick moves:</p>
<p><strong>A. LinkedIn scan (5 minutes)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Search <em>“Berkeley Research Group Second Sight Associate Implementation”</em> and look at people holding:
<ul>
<li>“Technical Implementation Manager” (TIM)</li>
<li>“Associate, Implementation”</li>
<li>“Healthcare Performance Improvement” / “Revenue Cycle”</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Look at their <strong>reporting lines &amp; groups</strong>. You’ll often see <strong>Implementation / Client Success / Product</strong> clustered together and <strong>HPI/Revenue Cycle</strong> clustered under <strong>Performance Improvement</strong>. If the Associate, Implementation profiles sit under “Client Implementation/Tech” and not under “HPI/PI,” that’s your signal it’s a separate team.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>B. Recruiter note (template below)</strong>
Send a short, professional note asking if <strong>Associate, Implementation</strong> sits under <strong>Second Sight Client Implementation (TIM org)</strong> or <strong>Performance Improvement</strong>. (Template in section 4.)</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Even if it reports up through BRG broadly, the <strong>day-to-day</strong> is different: Implementation = requirements, integrations, UAT, tickets, docs, and go‑lives. HPI = advisory/ops, RI/CDM, pricing/charge analytics, margin lift.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<h2>2) Why this role fits you better than the HPI RI/CDM interview</h2>
<p><strong>What tripped you up before:</strong> deep CDM governance and pricing-change cycles.<br>
<strong>What this new role emphasizes:</strong> implementation <em>execution</em>—requirements, integration mapping, ticket writing, configuration tracking, issue triage, client comms, and documentation.</p>
<p>That maps to what you already do:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Requirements &amp; translation:</strong> Cloudmed/FinThrive findings → Coding/RI actions; acceptance criteria; compliance write‑ups.</li>
<li><strong>Issue triage &amp; evidence:</strong> missing charges, rev codes, NCCI conflicts, supply mapping; you gather artifacts and route to the right owners.</li>
<li><strong>Config tracking &amp; UAT:</strong> Craneware/Lawson/Spacetrax mappings, testing in workflows, post-change validation.</li>
<li><strong>Documentation &amp; training:</strong> concise job aids, RI notes, and clear stakeholder comms.</li>
</ul>
<p>You’re stronger here—and you won’t be forced into granular CDM pricing/process questions.</p>
<hr>
<h2>3) Apply now, but protect the narrative</h2>
<p>When the ATS asks “Have you interviewed with us before?” say <strong>Yes</strong>, and use this one‑liner in the notes/open text:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>“I previously interviewed for the Healthcare Performance Improvement (Revenue Cycle) track in January. I’m now applying to Associate, Implementation because my strengths are hands‑on implementation delivery—requirements, integration mapping, ticket writing, UAT, documentation, and client onboarding. This role aligns more directly with my day‑to‑day experience in multi‑system healthcare implementations.”</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>This steers them to evaluate you on <strong>implementation</strong> competencies, not CDM advisory depth.</p>
<hr>
<h2>4) Message to recruiter / talent (paste‑ready)</h2>
<p>Subject: Reapplying — Associate, Implementation (Second Sight)</p>
<p>Hi [Name],<br>
I interviewed in <strong>January</strong> for the <strong>Healthcare Performance Improvement (Revenue Cycle)</strong> track. I’m now applying for <strong>Associate, Implementation</strong> on the Second Sight side. Can you confirm if this role sits under <strong>Client Implementation / Technical Implementation Managers</strong> rather than the PI/HPI group?</p>
<p>My background fits implementation execution—requirements gathering, integration/field mapping, JIRA ticket writing with clear acceptance criteria, UAT coordination, documentation, and client communications. I’ve delivered these across multi‑system hospital environments (Cloudmed, FinThrive, Craneware, Lawson/Spacetrax, Cerner context). I’d appreciate being considered for this implementation lane.</p>
<p>If helpful, I can share 1–2 brief project summaries that mirror your implementation lifecycle.<br>
Thanks so much,<br>
Leovie</p>
<hr>
<h2>5) How to answer “You interviewed here before—what changed?”</h2>
<blockquote>
<p><em>“The January interview targeted the HPI Revenue Cycle advisory lane with heavy CDM governance. I realized my strengths and recent wins are in implementation execution—turning requirements into tickets, mapping integrations, coordinating UAT, documenting decisions, and keeping workstreams moving with clear evidence and next steps. That’s exactly what Associate, Implementation emphasizes, so I’m focusing on this lane.”</em></p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<h2>6) Tailor bullets for your resume/application (plug-and-play)</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Coordinated</strong> cross‑functional implementation workstreams across RI, Coding, and Supply Chain, translating Cloudmed/FinThrive findings into <strong>JIRA-ready tickets</strong> with acceptance criteria; maintained decision logs, dependencies, and timelines.</li>
<li><strong>Mapped</strong> Lawson/Spacetrax item masters to CDM in Craneware; documented field mappings, performed UAT, and managed post‑load QA to ensure clean charge posting and claim routing.</li>
<li><strong>Led</strong> issue triage by gathering evidence (claims, charge router, NCCI edits), clarifying requirements, and routing to the correct team with replicable steps and proposed next actions; reduced recycling/aging by <strong>X%</strong>.</li>
<li><strong>Authored</strong> concise end‑user documentation and job aids; coordinated training and hypercare channels to stabilize go‑lives.</li>
<li><strong>Maintained</strong> RAID/action logs, weekly status updates, and implementation checklists to keep stakeholders aligned and deliverables on track.</li>
</ul>
<p>If you give me rough metrics (even ranges), I’ll quantify.</p>
<hr>
<h2>7) Expect these Associate, Implementation questions (and your talking points)</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>“How do you write a good ticket?”</strong><br>
<em>Clear business problem → impacted users/data → ‘as‑is’ vs ‘to‑be’ → fields/objects affected → acceptance criteria → test steps → attachments (screens, sample data, error IDs).</em></li>
<li><strong>“How do you manage requirements drift?”</strong><br>
<em>Baseline in a living spec; version control; change log with impact; confirm priority in backlog grooming.</em></li>
<li><strong>“Walk me through data mapping.”</strong><br>
<em>Source → target → field types/constraints → transformation rules → edge cases → sample records → validation queries → reconciliation checks.</em></li>
<li><strong>“How do you keep workstreams moving?”</strong><br>
<em>Daily/weekly cadence; unblockers list; evidence-based triage; explicit owners+dates; escalations only with options.</em></li>
<li><strong>“How do you handle unfamiliar domains?”</strong><br>
<em>Domain decompose → glossary → sample records → sequence diagrams → confirm with SMEs; ship small increments + verify with UAT.</em></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2>8) Should you mention the previous stumble on CDM?</h2>
<p>Only if asked. If they do:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>“Great learning for me—CDM advisory depth is valuable, but my strengths are implementation mechanics. That’s why I’m targeting Associate, Implementation where I’ve delivered repeatedly.”</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Short, confident, forward-looking.</p>
<hr>
<h2>9) Next steps I can do for you (fast turnaround)</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Tailored resume</strong> for Associate, Implementation (Second Sight/BRG flavor)</li>
<li><strong>One-page project sheet</strong> aligned to their lifecycle (kickoff → reqs → mapping → tickets → UAT → go‑live → hypercare)</li>
<li><strong>Mock Q&amp;A</strong> specific to Associate, Implementation (tickets, mappings, evidence, triage, docs)</li>
</ul>
<p>Want me to produce the resume + 1‑pager now? If yes, share any rough metrics (e.g., “reduced missed charges by ~15%,” “supported 6 sites,” “cut issue turnaround from 10→3 days”), and I’ll finalize.</p>
