87ej0 freluf8 f1yggaq6 f2i3chp f1151osp florpoh f35kzfz ftp9m57 f1e288vi fz62hnz fixvuys f1nmofwh fc1c6mv f18a2er7 fhvkrdl fhxnn68 f1oce4bo fvhlfan f7tc0t0 f1ngf1n2 ffrzq6x f1yjiq2m f1aqdgql f1huvaf f10ij78l f1k94sa4 fkmfumq f1jvzkyl f1eu24ob f1xbfc1f fmf0lwf f107dsy8 f3w566c f4648sl f13zpkng f7unjfp f8p1rz fzu6h1w f1i1bi6h f1smo7hi f1sk1xod f1kgogdq f1gjktkp ft608jz f19dd9cz fg3xr24 fhd155k f1b8gl2e fg4b9ou flb4lo fdicbfk fgwcyh1 f1jbds0d f1fb9uea f1stuka4 fcrtu6g fwqh0xn f11w66yg f6e0e65 f1vvgu0 f1607507 f1m9bycv f1ntoah8 f1b694rt faql4r2 fpjuhzh fmavl6h"><p>You’re right to question it — <strong>it’s a remote job, so why ask for location preferences?</strong><br>
This is VERY common with consulting firms and companies like BRG/Second Sight, even for remote roles.</p>
<p>Here’s exactly why they do it <strong>and what YOU should select</strong> so you don’t get screened out.</p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ <strong>Why a Remote Job Still Asks for Location Preference</strong></h1>
<p>You aren’t doing anything wrong — this is normal for Implementation + Consulting orgs.</p>
<p>They ask because:</p>
<h3><strong>1. They have “hub cities” for travel, onboarding, or team alignment</strong></h3>
<p>Even remote employees are often <em>mapped</em> to a city for:</p>
<ul>
<li>occasional on-site events</li>
<li>quarterly team meetings</li>
<li>client visits</li>
<li>alignment to a specific office/team</li>
</ul>
<p>These cities act as anchor points.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>2. They use this to segment candidates into “markets”</strong></h3>
<p>Even if fully remote, they still categorize hires by:</p>
<ul>
<li>Time zone</li>
<li>Team distribution</li>
<li>Client region coverage</li>
<li>Payroll/state requirements</li>
</ul>
<p>You’re in <strong>Mountain Time</strong>, so picking a city that aligns with MT or CT helps.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>3. Some clients require staff “mapped” to certain regions</strong></h3>
<p>Implementation teams may be assigned by region even when working from home.</p>
<hr>
<h3><strong>4. It helps them plan travel budgets</strong></h3>
<p>If you’re mapped to:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Phoenix</strong></li>
<li><strong>Salt Lake City</strong></li>
<li><strong>Las Vegas</strong>
You become a closer travel candidate for West/Midwest clients.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ <strong>What YOU should select</strong></h1>
<p>Since you’re in <strong>Colorado Springs (Mountain Time)</strong> and the role is remote:</p>
<h3>✔️ Pick cities that match your time zone or nearest travel hubs:</h3>
<p><strong>Recommended:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Phoenix, AZ</strong></li>
<li><strong>Salt Lake City, UT</strong></li>
<li><strong>Las Vegas, NV</strong></li>
<li><strong>Dallas, TX</strong> (central to many client locations)</li>
</ul>
<p>Any of these will be “safe” and will not affect your candidacy.</p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ DO NOT leave it blank — it will hurt you</h1>
<p>The ATS will often auto-reject or mark incomplete.<br>
Just pick the cities closest to your region/time zone.</p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ Want to be extra safe?</h1>
<p>Select <strong>Phoenix</strong> AND <strong>Salt Lake City</strong>.<br>
These are the most “neutral” for MT candidates.</p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ What NOT to do</h1>
<ul>
<li>Don’t pick NYC, LA, or Boston unless you want East or West Coast meeting schedules.</li>
<li>Don’t select only one city if the form allows multiples; multiple selections expand your match.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ Quick answer you can copy:</h1>
<blockquote>
<p>Since this is a remote role, I’m available nationwide. My preferred hubs are Phoenix, Salt Lake City, Las Vegas, and Dallas.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
