6g fwqh0xn f11w66yg f6e0e65 f1vvgu0 f1607507 f1m9bycv f1ntoah8 f1b694rt faql4r2 fpjuhzh fmavl6h"><p>I hear you — <strong>and NO, not all SaaS companies use Ashby.</strong><br>
It <em>feels</em> like that only because:</p>
<h3>✔️ You’ve applied to a specific <em>type</em> of SaaS company</h3>
<p>Most early‑stage and mid‑stage startups (Series A–C) use Ashby because it’s:</p>
<ul>
<li>Cheap</li>
<li>Fast to set up</li>
<li>Has prebuilt hiring templates</li>
<li>Requires zero HR expertise</li>
<li>Popular among YC‑style companies</li>
</ul>
<p>So you’re seeing it <strong>over and over</strong> because you’re applying in the SAME cluster of companies.</p>
<h3>✔️ Ashby = a <em>tool</em></h3>
<p>Not an indicator of the quality of the company.</p>
<p>Some amazing companies use Ashby.<br>
Some dumpster‑fire companies also use Ashby.</p>
<p>The tool isn’t the problem — the <strong>company’s hiring culture</strong> is.</p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ Why you feel like “almost all” SaaS companies use Ashby</h1>
<p>Because of THIS pattern:</p>
<h3><strong>You’re applying to:</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>Implementation Specialist</li>
<li>CS/PS roles</li>
<li>Solutions Consultant</li>
<li>SaaS onboarding</li>
<li>Technical PM/Implementation</li>
</ul>
<h3><strong>And those teams are usually in smaller or mid‑size SaaS companies.</strong></h3>
<p>Those companies don’t have HR departments → they outsource to Ashby.</p>
<p>So you’re constantly seeing:</p>
<ul>
<li>6‑step interview flows</li>
<li>Mock calls</li>
<li>VP rounds</li>
<li>Adoption scenarios</li>
<li>Technical drills</li>
<li>Customer success exercises</li>
</ul>
<p>Because that’s how Ashby’s <em>default</em> template is designed.</p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ But here’s the REAL truth:</h1>
<h2><strong>🔥 The big, stable, high‑paying SaaS companies DON’T do this.</strong></h2>
<p>Companies like:</p>
<ul>
<li>Salesforce</li>
<li>Workday</li>
<li>ServiceNow</li>
<li>Intuit</li>
<li>HubSpot</li>
<li>DocuSign</li>
<li>ZoomInfo</li>
<li>Adobe</li>
<li>Oracle</li>
<li>SAP</li>
<li>Snowflake</li>
<li>Tableau</li>
<li>Atlassian</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>DO NOT use Ashby</strong><br>
and<br>
<strong>DO NOT have 6–8 interview rounds for non‑engineering roles.</strong></p>
<p>Their interview process is:</p>
<h3>✔️ 1 recruiter call</h3>
<h3>✔️ 1 hiring manager</h3>
<h3>✔️ 1 mock/demo</h3>
<h3>✔️ Offer</h3>
<p>Two weeks maximum.</p>
<p>These companies have:</p>
<ul>
<li>Real HR teams</li>
<li>Real interview training</li>
<li>Defined job levels</li>
<li>Career progression</li>
<li>Less chaos</li>
<li>Lower turnover</li>
</ul>
<p>Startups?<br>
Completely different world.</p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ So the answer is:</h1>
<h3><strong>You are seeing Ashby everywhere because of your target job type — NOT because all SaaS companies are like this.</strong></h3>
<p>You’re applying in a part of SaaS where:</p>
<ul>
<li>High turnover</li>
<li>Underpaid roles</li>
<li>Poor structure</li>
<li>DIY HR systems</li>
<li>Long interview loops<br>
Are unfortunately common.</li>
</ul>
<p>But this is <strong>not</strong> the SaaS world — just a segment of it.</p>
<hr>
<h1>⭐ Want to shift into the good SaaS companies?</h1>
<p>I can help you redirect your job search toward:</p>
<h3>✔️ enterprise SaaS</h3>
<h3>✔️ mature companies</h3>
<h3>✔️ stable org structures</h3>
<h3>✔️ fair interview processes</h3>
<h3>✔️ fewer hoops</h3>
<h3>✔️ higher pay</h3>
<h3>✔️ better retention</h3>
<h3>✔️ predictable career paths</h3>
<p>If you tell me:
👉 the kind of role you actually want<br>
👉 your salary target<br>
👉 how much you’re willing to learn tech</p>
<p>I can give you a list of <strong>20–30 GOOD SaaS companies</strong> and tailor your résumé for those roles.</p>
<p>Just tell me:<br>
